{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595305"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:02:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:02:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15348"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15348"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.06,0.12,0.3,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8039"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70418"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8039"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15348"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55882"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19525"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19528"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70418"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA child presents to the emergency department with recurring abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following characteristics most strongly suggests a non-organic cause of abdominal pain in children?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Periumbilical pain that does not radiate","Right lower quadrant pain","Pain that wakes the child from sleep","Pain associated with weight loss","Pain that worsens with movement"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe location and characteristics of abdominal pain can help distinguish between organic and non-organic causes in children:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeriumbilical pain that does not radiate\u003C/strong\u003E is typical of functional or non-organic abdominal pain in children\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight lower quadrant pain\u003C/strong\u003E suggests organic pathology such as appendicitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPain that wakes the child from sleep\u003C/strong\u003E is concerning for organic pathology\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPain associated with weight loss\u003C/strong\u003E suggests underlying organic disease such as inflammatory bowel disease or coeliac disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPain that worsens with movement\u003C/strong\u003E suggests peritoneal inflammation and organic pathology\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOrganic causes of abdominal pain usually present with more specific locations and associated symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-organic abdominal pain in children typically presents with periumbilical pain that does not radiate and often improves with distraction","Organic causes of abdominal pain usually present with well-localised pain away from the umbilicus","Pain characteristics and associated symptoms help distinguish between organic and non-organic causes in paediatric abdominal pain"],"references":["Reust CE, Williams A. Acute Abdominal Pain in Children. Am Fam Physician. 2016 May 15;93(10):830-6. PMID: 27175718.","Lee WH, O\u0027Brien S, Skarin D, Cheek JA, Deitch J, Nataraja R, Craig S, Borland ML; PREDICT. Pediatric Abdominal Pain in Children Presenting to the Emergency Department. Pediatr Emerg Care. 2021 Dec 1;37(12):593-598. doi: 10.1097/PEC.0000000000001789. PMID: 30870338.","Raymond M, Marsicovetere P, DeShaney K. Diagnosing and managing acute abdominal pain in children. JAAPA. 2022 Jan 1;35(1):16-20. doi: 10.1097/01.JAA.0000803624.08871.5f. PMID: 34908557.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55882"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15348"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55882"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T07:50:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T08:50:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8039"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70418"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/ta